social_posts.post_text: Always amazed by the eagles majestic beauty 🦅 #Alaska #eagles #baldeagle #wildlife

Living in my camper has taught me to own less things. That could be hard at times since I like to stay active in the outdoors. I travel light with the help of @storquest as I store 
the gear that I don't need for that certain trip. Owning a storage unit has made camper life a breeze. #makeroomforawesome

I have had the amazing opportunity to go camping around various bucket list destinations in Alaska. One of the most memorable experiences I had was exploring this epic ice cave. It was truly a breathtaking experience that I will never forget. The blue and white hues of the ice walls and the way the light reflected off the ice was mesmerizing. It was definitely one of the highlights of my trip and I’m so thankful to have had a chance to explore such a unique and beautiful place.

Driving my camper during this Alaska Winter has been such an incredible experience. I love being able to take in the beauty of the snow covered landscape while staying warm. The cold weather brings its own unique challenges, but I’m learning how to adapt and make the most of my time here.

I must say, cold nights certainly have their charm. The crisp, cool air and the majestic views that accompany them make for an unforgettable experience. I'm always in awe of the beauty of nature, and these cold nights provide a unique opportunity to appreciate it.

The wood bison. These majestic creatures were once a common sight in the state, but their population was decimated by overhunting and habitat destruction. Thankfully, conservation efforts have been successful in bringing them back to their native homeland. Wood bison are now thriving in Alaska and can be found in a variety of habitats, from wetlands to boreal forests. With the help of dedicated conservationists, these majestic animals will continue to be a part of the Alaskan landscape for generations to come.

No matter what Mother Nature throws my way, I can always count on my @jackeryusa power station to make my camping trips easier and more enjoyable. It has become an essential part of my camping gear, and with just one charge, I'm able to keep my fridge running all night or my laptop charger going for the entire week. With this reliable power station, I can make the most of my camping trips, no matter what the weather throws at me. Found ourselves sharing the trail with a big brown bear.  We acted cautiously and responsibly, ensuring that the bear was aware of our presence in order to avoid startling it. We were pleased to have the opportunity to observe the bear in its natural habitat and take in the beauty of the moment. #Alaska #wildlife

The beauty of Winter in Alaska. Although the cold weather can be hard to handle at times, it does offer a great reward. From the snow covered mountains to the magical nights under the Aurora, I am reminded of how lucky I am to be here. #Alaska #photography
Surreal moments while driving through Thompson pass, Alaska. They say it is the snowiest place in the entire state, and we were fortunate enough to be able to visit during the peak of winter.

Stoked to embark on a new adventure. I am incredibly thankful to @Allnipponairways for providing me with the opportunity to explore some of the most stunning areas of Japan. I am especially excited to visit Mt. Fuji, Nagano, and Tokyo. These places have always been high on my list and I look forward to learning about the culture, history, and experiencing the unique atmosphere that each of these places has to offer. #ExperienceANA #ANApartner

I’ve landed in Japan! I had the pleasure of flying business class with @allnipponairways and I have to say that it was the best flight I’ve ever been on. The food was great, the pod was comfortable and the service was top-notch. ⁣
 ⁣
Since my arrival, I have been exploring the cities of Tokyo and Osaka. The vibrant colors, great food, and friendly people have exceeded my expectations.⁣
 ⁣
Now that we’ve explored the cities, I am excited to explore the nature side of Japan.⁣
#ANApartner #ExperienceANA

When I learned I would be traveling to Japan with @allnipponairways, visiting Nagano to experience the snow monkeys immediately came to mind as a must-visit destination. After seeing pictures of them in travel magazines, I couldn’t wait to witness them in person.⁣
⁣
These fascinating creatures are known for their love of hot springs and can be found soaking in the warm waters of Nagano during the winter months. Being in the moment with them made me feel like I was living out a traveler’s dream. This experience should be on the itinerary of anyone traveling to Japan. #ANApartner #ExperienceANA
Same spot, different season. I’m a big fan of fall colors but there’s something special about experiencing the northern lights. What do you guys think ?

flying over Knik glacier with my friends at @alaskahelicoptertours. It was truly an epic experience and one of the highlights of my winter in Alaska. While I’ve seen many incredible things during my time here, this one definitely ranks high on the list.

Japan is a country that has something for everyone. As someone who enjoys lively cities, I was surprised to discover the beauty of Japan's natural landscapes. One thing that stood out to me is the abundance of mountains and picturesque nature throughout the country. 
 
Overall, if and when you visit Japan, I highly recommend taking the time to explore Japan’s natural wonders. In collaboration with @Allnipponairways #ANApartner #experienceANA

I recently returned from a wonderful trip to Japan where I had the opportunity to work with @allnipponairways. During my travels, I discovered some incredible photo spots that I would like to share with you. If you plan on visiting Japan, be sure to check out my top 5 favorites:⁣
⁣
1. Arashiyama bamboo forest: Arrive early to avoid the crowds. ⁣
2. Jigokudani monkey park: Best in the colder months when the monkeys are bathing in hot spring. ⁣
3. Mt. Fuji: Spring time can be a bit busy but well worth it. Cherry blossoms season is beautiful in Mt.Fuji. ⁣
4. Togakushi shrine: Plan for a full day. The big trees are will be a nice reward after the journey to Togakushi. ⁣
5. Nara: Nara is home to many deer, which are considered sacred, and roam freely throughout the city.⁣
#ExperienceANA #ANApartner ⁣

Grizzly bear encounters are a common thing here in the summer. As winter comes to an end, the days are getting longer and the weather is slowly warming up. With the arrival of spring, grizzly bears will soon be waking up from hibernation. This means that we must be cautious while on the trail to avoid any potential encounters with these powerful animals. Despite the excitement of exploring the wilderness, it is important to remember the potential dangers and take necessary precautions. Stay safe out there ! #alaska #travelalaska

Spring has arrived and I’ve been enjoying observing the transition from season to season. The days are gradually becoming longer, the snow is slowly melting away and the ice on the lakes beginning to break off. The season that brought me back to Alaska in the first place is almost here and I’m excited for another epic summer. #Alaska #travelalaska

Saying goodbye to nights like these. The days are getting longer day by day which makes the aurora harder to see. Either way, I’m happy to exchange these views for warmer days. #alaska #travelalaska #auroraborealis

Taking a moment to appreciate the slower days on the road. Living life in my camper has taught me that it’s not always about capturing the perfect photo, but rather enjoying the moment. There’s no need to rush, as some of the best memories happen when we take our time. #Alaska #camperlife
My view for the past 5 days now. Thought this would be a good place to set up camp while I get some work done. I’ll give this one 5 stars. #alaska #travelalaska

The locals were right about false spring. I thought I had finally made it through winter, but the joke was on me. Just when I started to get excited about warmer weather, more snow came pouring down. It's like Mother Nature is playing a cruel game with us. But hey, I'm not giving up hope just yet. Maybe this time spring will actually stick around. Fingers crossed! #alaska #travelalaska

Restoring an 8 year old axe. This axe was in rough shape so I decided to visit @greatnorthernknives here in Alaska to give it life again. I asked if I could film the process and they allowed me to go back into the workshop to film the magic behind the work they do. Happy with the results and excited to start chopping some wood. #supportsmallbusiness #alaska #travelalaska

I just spent the last two weeks camping in the same spot, putting the finishing touches on the camper. It was a bit of work, but we managed to get it done. I took a few breaks here and there to watch the planes go by. I gotta say, it was a pretty sweet view to get some work done. #alaska

This device effectively keeps the mosquitos away, allowing me to enjoy the outdoors without any issues. It’s an essential part of my gear and I never leave without it. #thermacellpartner #ad #alaska
Coffee in the mountains just hits different. I think it has a lot more to do than the glacier water used to make this coffee. #alaska #coffee

There's nothing quite like an unexpected sunset. You know, those moments when the sky is so cloudy that you're sure the sun has given up for the day. But then, out of nowhere, it appears. It's like magic. #alaska #travelalaska #camper #poptopcamper
Breakfast with friends. It doesn’t get much better than that. #alaska

Another successful trip with @majormarinetours. Seeing a glacier on the Kenai fjords has been on my bucket list for quite some time. Happy to be able to scratch that off my list. #alaska #travelalaska

Denali National Park is truly a special place. It is evident as you journey through the park that it has been carefully maintained and protected. It's important to treasure these wild spaces, which is why I am happy to be partnering with @parksproject. As a company, their goal is to protect and preserve parklands for generations to come by educating, advocating, donating, volunteering, and activating supporters to get involved in conservation. Since 2014, they've donated $2.5 million back to parklands across the country. #parksproject #leaveitbetterthanyoufoundit #denalinationalpark #alaska
Summer vibes. Lakes are no longer frozen and I can do more of this 🚣🏻‍♀️ #alaska #travelalaska

⁣

#Alaska #travelalaska #canon #beautifuldestinations #glacier #mountainlife

The benefits of backpacking instead of day hiking: ⁣
1. You get to wake up for sunrise. ⁣
2. You might get the place all to yourself. ⁣
3. More time means different lighting conditions. ⁣
4. You get to soak it all in. ⁣
⁣
I’m sure I missed a few but these are some important ones for me. Stay safe out there !⁣
⁣
#Alaska #travelslaska #mountainlife #beautifuldestinations #backpacking #hiking #packrafting #rafting #tentcamping

Wide lens vs telephoto lens. ⁣
16mm, 200mm & 400mm. ⁣
⁣
I use wide angle lenses to capture an overall scene. Perfect for when I want to show more mountains. ⁣
⁣
Telephoto lenses make the background appear bigger and much closer to foreground subjects while focusing on the details. They give me a different and a more unique perspective. Also, a great way to get close to wildlife without putting your life in danger. ⁣
⁣
#alaska #travelalaska #canon #canonphotography #photography #mountainlife

Can’t believe I’m here. Driving the opposite way from where I should be heading. I convinced myself to chase fall colors and somehow I just kept driving further north. 

I’m now a few hours away from the Arctic circle but something tells me that that’s not the end of my drive. Maybe I’ll drive to the Arctic Ocean. I really don’t have anywhere else to be so why not. 

#yukon #travelyukon #canon #explorecanada #camperlife #truckcamper #camper #bautifuldestinations

What a journey this has been. Last minute trip to the Arctic circle. After several days of driving, we finally made it. 

The road does not end here. I’ve been encouraged by many of you guys to just keep on going. To keep driving north. Now that I’ve passed the Arctic circle, the Arctic Ocean is on my mind. It’s only a few more days of driving. 

#arcticcircle #yukon #exploreyukon #explorecanada #canada #camperlife #truckcamper #mountainlife

The Arctic circle ! Been driving for countless days and finally made it. 

I convinced myself to keep driving until the road ends at the ocean. Many of you guys have suggested that I should jump in the ocean. Not sure if I’m brave enough for that but I might just have to. 

#yukon #exploreyukon #explorecanada #camper #camperlife #mountainlife #canada #truckcamperlife #truckcamperlife

A lot of you suggested that I should jump in the water once I got to the Arctic Ocean. I wasn’t too stoked on that, knowing how cold it would be. I knew that the weather would be cold but I didn’t expect it to be “arctic cold”. 

Now that I’ve driven to the end of the road, what’s next ? I guess I’ll drive back down and enjoy the season transition from summer to fall and hopefully catch some early northern lights. 

#arcticcircle #canada #dempsterhighway #trucklife #roadtrip #tuktoyaktuk #arcticocean #northwestterritories #explorecanada

Fall has arrived up north. It’s a good sign that the days will start getting colder and that I need to start driving south. It’s also a great time to see the Aurora and another great reason to stick around a little longer. 

#alaska #travelalaska #autumn #mountainlife #beautifuldestinations #nature

Surreal morning surrounded by ice. It’s hard to pick a favorite place in Alaska but I can say that this makes the list on my top 5.

Now that we’ve made it to the top of the world and jumped into the Arctic Ocean, we’re making our way back south. Not really sure where I will be tomorrow or the next day but I have a feeling that it’s going to be pretty epic.

Disclaimer: This is not Baja

Putting my #columbiaeyewear to the test on my drive back south. I can say that they are made for comfort and can endure any adventure. @columbia1938 #columbia #ad

Fall is officially here! Got to enjoy the peak of the season while backpacking tombstone. 27 steep miles (43 kilometers) and rewarding views. 

We were also the last people to backpack tombstone this year. The park is now closed for the year and not many people wanted to go on the last days due to bad weather. That only meant that we had it all to ourselves. I may not have gotten the best conditions but it was well worth it. 

#yukon #explorecanada #travelyukon #tombstone #beautifuldestinations #backpacking #fall #canada

Not Patagonia, this is Canada. I’ve heard that people call this place the Patagonia of the north. I never quite understood why. Now I understand. 

#yukon #tombstoneterritorialpark #explorecanada #travelyukon #canada #beautifuldestinations

Not Canada, this is Patagonia. Complete oposite side of the world from where I’m at but yet so similar. I think they should call Patagonia the “Tombstone of the south”. 

Looking back at these old photos from my trip down there in 2019. I think next time I’ll drive down instead of fly. It’s a long journey but I know it’s worth it. 

#patagonia #autumn #canon #beautifuldestinations #fall #mountainlife

This has to be my new favorite thing. Wrapping myself in winter clothes, a warm blanket and laying on a hammock while enjoying the Aurora borealis. 

I stayed up until 5am looking up at the sky. I always feel guilty going inside while the lights are out so I just stay awake to make sure I don’t miss anything. Yes, I’m losing sleep but I think it’s worth it. 

#yukon #travelyukon #exploreyukon #canada #truckcamper #auroraborealis #northernlights

I've witnessed 3 seasons in 3 weeks here in northern Yukon, Canada. Summer, Autumn and the beginning of Winter. The colors are past peak and snow is starting to hit the mountains. Not trying to spend time in the snow just yet so it's time to head further south.

#yukon #travelyukon #canada #explorecanada #autumn #mountainlife

A dirty camper is a happy camper. It means that I’ve been putting it through what it’s built for. Built for adventure. 

We ended up parking on the side of the road to call it home for the night. I’ve been driving a lot and have to figure out where to head next. Maybe Southeast Alaska? 

#camperlife #campertruck #yukon #travelyukon #explorecanada #canada

In between two seasons. Here’s a glimpse of what fall up north is looking like. A bit of snow and lots of color. 

#yukon #travelyukon #explorecanada #canada #mountainlife #beautifuldestinations

We’re heading back to Alaska ! It’s only been 4 weeks since I left and I’m already heading back. This time I’ll be exploring a new region. Southeast Alaska 🫶🏻

#explorebc #canada #truckcamper #canon #camperlife #alaska

A full month in Yukon, Canada. What an adventure it has been ! Sad to finish this chapter in our journey but also stoked for what’s ahead. 

I told myself I’d use my camera every single day and I kept that promise. Here are a few highlights from our time up north. 

#yukon #travelyukon #exploreyouryukon #canon #canonusa

Window seat with a scenic view. I’ll take this over first class any day.

I’ve been in @haines.alaska for 2 weeks now. Doing what locals do and enjoying what this town has to offer. I think that’s the best way to really enjoy the place you’re traveling to. 

#alaska #travelalaska #haines #mountains #mountainlife

Today marks 6 years with Juneau. I’m not sure when his birthday is since he was a stray dog from the pound when I adopted him. For that reason, we celebrate this day as a special day. 

Another reason why today is special is because we are currently traveling through Juneau, Alaska. His name has some great meaning which I will talk about on a later post. 

Anyway, happy adoption day Juneau 🐶

#alaska #travelalaska #campingwithdogs #truckcamper

I hear that it’s been snowing in some places already. Not sure if it’s right on time but it seems a little early. Either way, I feel like I’ve had an eventful summer and I’m ready for that snow to hit. 

Also, thank you for rotating your phone 🫶🏻

#alaska #travelalaska #truckcamper #mountainlife

Holding on to the little time we have left here in Alaska. We’re currently in Juneau while we wait for our ferry to take us to the lower 48. ⛴️

 #alaska #travelalaska #juneau #traveljuneau #mountainlife

I apologize for making you flip your phone or tilt your head. I like to thank you for that every time I post a sideways shot. 

Some moments can make you feel like you’re in a dream. Paddling through these blue waters was definitely one of them. I had to remind myself that I’m actually here and I have this video to prove it.

“you should never go to Alaska as a young man because you’ll never be satisfied with any other place as long as you live.”
-John Muir 

I can feel what John Muir meant by that. I’ve never felt more like myself as I do here in Alaska. After 15 months in this state, I can say this place feels like home. A home away from home.

This is my “sorry mom” video. 

I kept hearing a gushing sound as I walked deeper into the ice cave. I thought maybe there could be a river nearby. I look down and realized that the river was actually below me and I could see through the ice. 

My initial instinct was to stand still and figure out a safe way to take my next steps. I’m not sure how thick the ice was but I wasn’t trying to find out. Too many things that can go wrong here. 

I’ve heard someone say “Alaska is great! You can walk out your front door and die.” I can see what they meant by that. 

#Alaska #travelalaska #icecave #mountainlife #alaskalife

I feel like I need to answer the main questions that I have been getting from lots of you guys. How do I travel the way I do and what do I do for a living ? 

The most expensive part was getting started. Building a set up that you’re comfortable with that you can call home. After that, there are many ways to travel on a budget. 

I’ve been in Alaska for 15 months now so I really haven’t moved around too much. I can’t say I’ve spent too much on gas. Food? I don’t eat at restaurants and I actually fished for half of the summer. All that salmon has allowed me to just live off that while not spending too much at the grocery store. 

As for my job: I am a photographer and work with outdoor brands. Having a home on wheels that I can park in epic spots while I wait for good weather is a big part of my process. It goes hand in hand. 

I’m not saying that you need to be a photographer to live this lifestyle. There are many ways you can work remotely while living on the road. I think that having starlink (wifi) on the road has opened up many doors for people that are aiming for life on the road. 

I hope this helps a bit. Feel free to ask any other questions in the comments. I’ll be pinning the top questions for others to read. 

#alaska #travelalaska #camperlife #truckcamper #lifeontheroad

The day that my camper turned into a boat. I thought that I had lost my camper at this point. Left tires up in the air and tipped to the side as the tide came in. 

We were forced to wait 4 hours until the tide dropped so we could try again. Luckily, my friend @nickbondarev came to the rescue and pulled us out of this messy situation. 

Lesson of the day: Watch out for king tides & respect the ocean. 

#truckcamper #camperlife #washington

I’ve waited a month to see this in person. King tide! A combination of high tide along with big waves. It isn’t everyday that you get to see huge waves crashing infront of you which is why so many people come out here to see it. 

This event felt a bit like surfing. You wake up early, go line up and hope to catch the biggest wave. Not sure if this was the biggest wave of the day but it sure did feel that way. 

Next king tide: January 20th - 22nd 2024. 

A few tips: Arrive early, bring a tripod, dress warm, prepare for possible rain & be nice to others.

Did you know that by cutting down your own Christmas tree, you can help the environment? I always thought it was the opposite until I found out that the US forest service encourages it. Here is what they had to say about that : 

“the elimination of trees actually helps forest health. Experts identify sections that would benefit from the thinning of small circumference trees in dense areas. Removing these trees in designated areas helps other trees grow larger and can open areas that provide food for wildlife. "

A $5 permit is required and make sure that you understand and follow all guidelines before heading out.
